Chapter 9 Part II: Ensemble Models¶

Bagging (Bootstrap Aggregation)¶

Bootstrap is a resampling technique used in statistics and machine learning to estimate the sampling distribution of a statistic or to assess uncertainty in a dataset. Starting with the original data, we draw multiple random samples with replacement, each called a bootstrap sample, and each sample has the same size as the original dataset. This process creates many similar but slightly different datasets, allowing us to estimate variability, bias, and confidence intervals of model estimates.

While CART models have many advantages, their main weakness is high variance: small changes in the training data can lead to very different trees. Bagging (short for Bootstrap Aggregating) addresses this by building multiple models on bootstrap samples and averaging their predictions.
Its an ensemble learning technique designed to reduce variance and improve predictive stability and accuracy for both regression and classification problems. Bagging is especially effective for unstable models like decision trees. By combining many such trees, the ensemble produces smoother, more reliable predictions. However, this comes at the cost of reduced interpretability, since the final model is an average of many trees rather than a single, transparent decision tree.

Mathematical Representation¶

Suppose we have a training dataset $D = \{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^n$.
Bagging generates $B$ bootstrap samples $D^{*(1)}, D^{*(2)}, \ldots, D^{*(B)}$, each drawn with replacement from $D$.

For each bootstrap sample, a base model (e.g., decision tree) $f^{*(b)}(x)$ is fitted.

The final bagging predictor is the average (for regression) or majority vote (for classification) of all models:

  • Regression: $$ \hat{f}_{\text{bag}}(x) = \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^{B} f^{*(b)}(x) $$

  • Classification: $$ \hat{C}_{\text{bag}}(x) = \text{majority vote}\left( f^{*(1)}(x), f^{*(2)}(x), \ldots, f^{*(B)}(x) \right) $$

As $B \to \infty$, the variance of $\hat{f}_{\text{bag}}(x)$ decreases, while the bias remains roughly the same, leading to improved generalization performance.

Algorithmic Steps for Bagging¶

  1. Input: Training dataset $D = \{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^n$, number of bootstrap samples $B$.
  2. For each $b = 1, 2, \ldots, B$:
    • Draw a bootstrap sample $D^{*(b)}$ by sampling $n$ observations with replacement from $D$.
    • Fit a base learner (e.g., a decision tree) $f^{*(b)}(x)$ using $D^{*(b)}$.
  3. Aggregate predictions:
    • For regression: average the predictions.
    • For classification: use majority vote across all models.
  4. Optionally evaluate model performance using Out-of-Bag (OOB) samples.

OOB (Out-of-Bag) Data and OOB Error¶

When building each tree in a bagging ensemble, the algorithm creates a bootstrap sample from the training data sampling with replacement to form a dataset of the same size as the original. Because some observations are selected multiple times, on average about 63.2% of the training observations appear in each bootstrap sample, while the remaining 36.8% are not selected. These unused observations are called the Out-of-Bag (OOB) samples. Each tree is trained only on its bootstrap sample, and the corresponding OOB data serves as a built-in validation set for that tree. The OOB error is then computed as the average prediction error of the ensemble on all OOB samples, providing an internal estimate of the models generalization performance without needing a separate validation set.

Metric Meaning Example Value Interpretation
OOB Error Average error rate on out-of-bag samples 0.215 21.5% of OOB samples misclassified
OOB Accuracy 1 - OOB Error 0.785 78.5% of OOB samples correctly classified

Advantages of Bagging

  1. Effective for Large Datasets
    Bagging performs especially well on large datasets. When data is abundant, the empirical distribution closely approximates the true population, allowing bootstrap resamples to better capture the underlying patterns and relationships.

  2. Versatility
    Bagging is not limited to a specific algorithmit can be applied to a variety of models (e.g., decision trees, regressions, neural networks), demonstrating strong flexibility across different machine learning methods.

  3. Variance Reduction
    The primary goal of bagging is to reduce variance. Under the assumption of independence, averaging over $B$ bootstrap samples reduces variance roughly by a factor of $1/B$, following the Central Limit Theorem.
    This results in more stable, less overfit predictions.

  4. Out-of-Bag (OOB) Evaluation
    Bagging naturally provides a built-in performance evaluation.
    For each bootstrap sample, about 36.8% of the data is left out (not selected)these are called Out-of-Bag samples.
    They act as a built-in test set, allowing accurate performance estimation without additional cross-validation.

Drawbacks of Bagging

  1. Loss of Interpretability
    The final model is an average of many trees, not a single interpretable decision tree.
    While accuracy often improves, understanding how predictions are made becomes more difficult.

  2. Increased Computational Cost
    Since bagging fits $B$ separate models, its computational cost is roughly $B$ times that of a single model.
    This may become significant for large datasets or limited computing resources.

  3. Correlation Among Base Models
    The variance reduction benefit of averaging depends on how independent the models are.
    If the individual trees are highly correlated (e.g., because of similar predictors or dominant features), the overall variance reduction is smaller.
    Hence, correlation among base models can limit baggings effectiveness.

Example: Bagging in R (Using ipred package)¶

Build a predictive model using bagging to classify the Species variable in the iris dataset. First, split the data into 80% training and 20% testing subsets. Using the training data, fit a CART model (rpart) with minsplit = 5, minbucket = 3, and maxdepth = 7, and record its accuracy. Next, apply the bagging() function from the ipred package with nbagg = 50 to build an ensemble of trees and compute the Out-of-Bag (OOB) error. Then, use the caret packages train() function with method = "treebag" and 10-fold cross-validation to fit another bagging model. Finally, evaluate and compare the predictive accuracy of the single CART model, the ipred bagging model, and the caret treebag model on the testing data, and briefly discuss which performs best and why.

  data = train.dat,

  1. Split the data into 80% training and 20% testing subsets using set.seed(527).
  2. Using the training data:
    • Fit a CART model (rpart) with minsplit = 5, minbucket = 3, and maxdepth = 7, and record its accuracy.

Random Forests¶

The Random Forest algorithm, introduced by Leo Breiman and Adele Cutler (2001), is one of the most powerful and widely used ensemble learning methods in machine learning. It extends the concept of Bagging (Bootstrap Aggregation) by adding an additional layer of randomness. Not only does each decision tree in the ensemble use a different bootstrap sample of the data, but at each split, the algorithm also considers a random subset of predictor variables.

This dual randomness, sampling both data points and features, produces a forest of diverse and uncorrelated trees. By aggregating their predictions, Random Forest achieves strong predictive performance, stability, and robustness, making it one of the best general-purpose algorithms for both classification and regression tasks.

The Random Forest algorithm combines the strength of multiple decision trees using both bootstrap sampling and random feature selection, resulting in a powerful, stable, and accurate ensemble model. It effectively reduces variance and overfitting compared to single decision trees and provides useful measures such as OOB error and feature importance. Although less interpretable and more computationally demanding, Random Forest remains a top choice for most applied machine learning problems due to its robustness, accuracy, and minimal tuning requirements.

How Random Forests Work

In a classification Random Forest, multiple decision trees are constructed using different random subsets of both the data and the features. Each tree acts as an independent classifier, producing its own prediction. The final prediction is made by majority vote across all trees.

For regression, the final prediction is the average of the predictions from all trees.

Algorithmic Steps

  1. Bootstrap Sampling
    Draw ( B ) bootstrap samples from the training data. Each sample is drawn with replacement, typically containing about 63% of the original data.

  2. Tree Construction (Random Feature Selection)
    For each bootstrap sample:

    • At every split, randomly select ( m ) out of the total ( p ) features (where ( m < p )).
    • The best split is determined only among those ( m ) features, introducing randomness and decorrelation among trees.

  3. Tree Growth
    Each tree is grown fully without pruning (max depth).

  4. Prediction Aggregation

    • Classification: use the majority vote among trees.
    • Regression: use the average of predicted values.

Let ( f_b(x) ) denote the prediction from the ( b )-th tree, for ( b = 1, 2, \ldots, B ).

  • Regression: [ \hat{f}{\text{RF}}(x) = \frac{1}{B} \sum{b=1}^{B} f_b(x) ]

  • Classification: [ \hat{C}_{\text{RF}}(x) = \text{majority vote} \big( f_1(x), f_2(x), \ldots, f_B(x) \big) ]

By averaging across many de-correlated trees, Random Forests achieve a large reduction in variance without a corresponding increase in bias.

Features of Random Forest

  • Aggregation of Multiple Decision Trees:
    Random Forest builds an ensemble of many decision trees, combining their predictions to create a single, more robust output.

  • Random Feature Selection:
    At each split, only a subset of predictors is considered, which reduces correlation between trees and improves generalization.

  • Inherent Out-of-Bag (OOB) Evaluation:
    About 36.8% of the observations are left out of each bootstrap sample. These are used to estimate the OOB error, which serves as an unbiased estimate of model accuracy without needing a separate test set.

Advantages of Random Forest¶

  • High Predictive Accuracy:
    Averaging many uncorrelated trees results in a powerful model that outperforms a single decision tree in most cases.

  • Built-in Validation (OOB Error):
    The OOB samples provide a natural estimate of test error, eliminating the need for cross-validation.

  • Robust to Overfitting:
    The randomness in both data sampling and feature selection prevents the model from memorizing noise.

  • Handles Large Feature Spaces:
    Works well with high-dimensional data and can estimate feature importance.

  • Resistant to Missing Data:
    Can maintain predictive power even when some predictors are missing.

Disadvantages of Random Forest¶

  • Loss of Interpretability:
    The ensemble nature makes it less transparent than a single decision tree.

  • Computational Cost:
    Training hundreds of trees can be computationally intensive, requiring more memory and processing power.

  • Limited Extrapolation in Regression:
    Like decision trees, random forests cannot predict beyond the range of observed data.

Random Forest Implementation in R¶

In R, the randomForest package (Breiman & Cutler) is commonly used to create Random Forest models.
The function randomForest() fits the model and provides built-in OOB error estimation and feature importance.

# Fit random forest model
fit.rf = randomForest(
  diabetes ~ ., 
  data = train.dat,
  ntree = 200,          # number of trees
  mtry = 2,             # number of features to try at each split
  importance = TRUE
)

# Print model summary
print(fit.rf)

#OOB error rate
cat("OOB Error Rate:", round(fit.rf$err.rate[nrow(fit.rf$err.rate), "OOB"] * 100, 2), "%\n")

# Predict on test data
pred.rf = predict(fit.rf, newdata = test.dat)
confusionMatrix(pred.rf, test.dat$diabetes)

# Feature importance plot
varImpPlot(fit.rf, main = "Variable Importance (Random Forest)")

The OOB error typically decreases and stabilizes as the forest grows. The elbow point indicates where adding more trees yields diminishing returns.

Key tuning hyperparameters for Random Forests¶

  1. ntree number of trees.

    • More trees variance and stabilize OOB error; compute grows roughly linearly.
    • Typical ranges: 3001000 (often 500 is fine once OOB error plateaus).

  2. mtry number of candidate predictors tried at each split.

    • Defaults: sqrt(p) (classification), p/3 (regression).
    • mtry = p bagging (trees become more correlated, higher variance).
    • mtry = 1 maximizes de-correlation but can increase bias.
    • Practical tip: search a small grid around the default (e.g., 50%).

  3. sampsize size of the bootstrap sample per tree.

    • Default: draws n rows with replacement; ~63.2% of rows are unique in each bootstrap sample (the rest are duplicates).
    • You may set a fraction (e.g., sampsize = 0.7*n) for faster training; smaller values bias, larger values variance/cost.
    • For classification, you can pass a vector to balance classes.

  4. nodesize minimum observations in a terminal node (controls tree depth).

    • Defaults: 1 (classification), 5 (regression).
    • Smaller deeper trees ( bias, variance). Larger shallower trees ( bias, variance).

  5. maxnodes hard cap on the number of terminal nodes.

    • Another knob to limit depth/complexity; leaving it NULL is common unless you need extra regularization.

General workflow: start with defaults, tune mtry first, then consider nodesize/sampsize; increase ntree until the OOB curve flattens.

Initial tuning with randomForest::tuneRF (regression)¶

The helper tuneRF() searches for a good mtry by tracking OOB error.

set.seed(6021)

# Response and predictors
y_train = train.dat$medv
x_train = train.dat[, setdiff(names(train.dat), "medv")]
y_test  = test.dat$medv
x_test  = test.dat[, setdiff(names(test.dat), "medv")]

#------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. Initial tuning of mtry using tuneRF
#------------------------------------------------------------
set.seed(6021)
p = ncol(x_train)

tune.out = tuneRF(
  x = x_train,
  y = y_train,
  mtryStart = floor(p/3),
  stepFactor = 1.5,
  improve = 0.01,
  ntreeTry = 400,
  trace = TRUE,
  plot = TRUE,
  doBest = FALSE
)

best.mtry = tune.out[which.min(tune.out[, "OOBError"]), "mtry"]
cat("\nBest mtry from tuneRF:", best.mtry, "\n")

#------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. Fit random forests with small grid search
#------------------------------------------------------------
ntree.grid = c(500, 1000)
nodesize.grid = c(5, 10, 20)

results = data.frame(ntree = integer(), mtry = integer(),
                     nodesize = integer(), OOB_MSE = numeric(),
                     OOB_R2 = numeric())

best.model = NULL
best.oob = Inf

for (nt in ntree.grid) {
  for (ns in nodesize.grid) {
    set.seed(6021)
    rf.fit = randomForest(
      x = x_train, y = y_train,
      ntree = nt,
      mtry = best.mtry,
      nodesize = ns,
      importance = TRUE,
      replace = TRUE,
      keep.inbag = TRUE
    )

    oob.mse = tail(rf.fit$mse, 1)
    oob.r2  = tail(rf.fit$rsq, 1)

    results = rbind(results,
                    data.frame(ntree = nt, mtry = best.mtry,
                               nodesize = ns, OOB_MSE = oob.mse,
                               OOB_R2 = oob.r2))

    if (oob.mse < best.oob) {
      best.oob = oob.mse
      best.model = rf.fit
    }
  }
}

cat("\nTuning Results (sorted by OOB_MSE):\n")
print(results[order(results$OOB_MSE), ])

#------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. Evaluate best model on test data
#------------------------------------------------------------
yhat = predict(best.model, newdata = x_test)
rmse = sqrt(mean((yhat - y_test)^2))
r2   = cor(yhat, y_test)^2

cat(sprintf("\nBest Model: ntree=%d, mtry=%d, nodesize=%d\n",
            best.model$ntree, best.model$mtry, best.model$nodesize))
cat(sprintf("OOB MSE=%.3f, OOB R2=%.3f\n",
            tail(best.model$mse, 1), tail(best.model$rsq, 1)))
cat(sprintf("Test RMSE=%.3f, Test R2=%.3f\n", rmse, r2))

#------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. Variable importance and partial dependence
#------------------------------------------------------------
varImpPlot(best.model, main = "Variable Importance (Random Forest)")

# Partial dependence for top variable
top.var = names(importance(best.model, type = 1))[which.max(importance(best.model, type = 1))]

#            main = paste("Partial Dependence on", top.var))
